<dl id="n53107p"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n53" href="#n53107p">N53 (VI.B.46)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n53all.htm#n53107p"> 107(p)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Poor Rube <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n53107p"><li>FW 328.01 </li><li><a href="../../flex/ma/lexma.htm#n53107p">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/ma/l39ma.htm#n53107p">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n53107p">MS BL 47479-162</ms> </li><li>JJA 54:279 <a name="mad6" href="../../FF/fdra/mda.htm#mad6">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/ma/mad6.htm#n53107p">Draft: II.3&sect;1.6</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">A ribald ditty among the college boys of the &apos;Sixties, celebrating the perils of that godless New York, and a forerunner of <i>The Bowery</i> and others of its kind, was <i>The Dark Girl Dressed in Blue</i>. Central Park is here the vicious circle, instead of the East Side, but the moral for provincial visitors is very much the same. Nothing gets a heartier laugh in the Sophisticated Metropolis to-day than the <mark>Poor Rube</mark> who falls for the most obvious chicanery. <font color="green">[The term &lsquo;a <mark>poor Rube</mark>&rsquo; was applied to an innocent visitor to New York that unwisely lacked a guide.]</font> <small> Sigmund Spaeth, <a name="REAW1" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#REAW1"><cite title="source">Read 'Em and Weep</cite></a> (1935) 86</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
